    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't just look, feel, and poke – triple check for breast cancer!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer identifies the three core components of the \"Triple Assessment\" for breast cancer, a standard diagnostic approach. This comprehensive strategy aims to maximize diagnostic accuracy and minimize unnecessary biopsies, ensuring a thorough evaluation of any suspicious breast lesion.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTriple assessment is a cornerstone in the evaluation of breast lesions, combining clinical, imaging, and pathological assessments. Clinical examination provides initial assessment of the lesion's characteristics, location, and regional lymph nodes. Mammography (often supplemented by ultrasound) offers detailed imaging of the breast tissue, identifying suspicious lesions, their extent, and guiding further intervention. Fine Needle Aspiration Cytology (FNAC) or core needle biopsy provides a tissue diagnosis, confirming malignancy or benignity. The combination of these three modalities significantly increases diagnostic sensitivity and specificity, guiding subsequent management decisions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): While history and clinical examination are crucial, mammogram alone as the third component misses the essential pathological confirmation, which is vital for definitive diagnosis.\nOption B (Incorrect): History and clinical examination are important, but FNAC alone as the third component without imaging (mammogram/USG) is incomplete for a comprehensive assessment of the breast, as imaging provides crucial information on lesion characteristics and extent.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option includes imaging (USG, mammogram) and pathology (FNAC) but omits the vital clinical examination, which provides essential context, guides imaging and biopsy, and assesses palpable findings.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Component | Description | Role in Triple Assessment |\n|---|---|---|\n| Clinical Examination | Palpation of breast and axilla, assessment of skin changes, nipple discharge. | Initial assessment, guides imaging and biopsy, evaluates palpable lesions. |\n| Imaging (Mammogram/USG) | Radiographic evaluation of breast tissue, lesion localization, characterization. | Detects non-palpable lesions, assesses extent, guides biopsy, characterizes masses. |\n| Pathology (FNAC/Core Biopsy) | Microscopic analysis of cells/tissue obtained from the lesion. | Definitive diagnosis of benign vs. malignant, guides treatment planning. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Triple assessment = Clinical + Imaging + Pathology.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, suspicious lesions often appear as spiculated masses, architectural distortion, or pleomorphic microcalcifications. Ultrasound can characterize masses as solid or cystic, assess vascularity, and precisely guide biopsies.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer Screening and Diagnosis (2023) consistently recommend a multi-modality approach, including clinical evaluation, imaging, and biopsy, for the assessment of breast lesions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | History, clinical examination and mammogram | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | History, clinical examination and FNAC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | USG, mammogram and FNAC | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Clinical examination, mammogram and FNAC | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Clinical examination, mammogram and FNAC** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
