    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Catching cancer early at 40 keeps life's chapters from getting blurry.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that routine screening mammography typically begins at 40 years of age for women of average risk. This recommendation is based on a careful balance of cancer incidence, screening efficacy, and the potential for false positives and overtreatment.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nStarting routine screening at age 40 allows for earlier detection of breast cancer in a population where incidence begins to rise significantly. At this age, the benefits of early detection, such as improved prognosis and less aggressive treatment, generally outweigh the risks associated with radiation exposure and false-positive results, especially for women of average risk. Mammography is the only screening tool proven to reduce breast cancer mortality.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 20 years is too young for routine screening mammography due to very low breast cancer incidence and higher breast density, which reduces mammography sensitivity and increases false positives.\nOption B (Incorrect): 30 years is generally too early for routine screening in average-risk women. Screening at this age is typically reserved for high-risk individuals based on genetic mutations or strong family history.\nOption D (Incorrect): 50 years is not the *start* of routine screening; rather, it's an age where screening continues, often annually or biennially, as breast cancer incidence further increases with age.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Age Group | Screening Recommendation (Average Risk) | Rationale |\n|---|---|---|\n| <40 years | Clinical breast exam, self-awareness | Low incidence, high breast density, radiation concerns |\n| 40-49 years | Annual mammography (ACR/ACS) | Incidence begins to rise, benefits outweigh risks |\n| 50-74 years | Annual/Biennial mammography (USPSTF/ACR/ACS) | Highest incidence, clear mortality benefit |\n| >75 years | Individualized decision | Based on health status, life expectancy, comorbidities |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Forty is the new fifty for breast cancer screening.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn a screening mammogram, a suspicious finding might appear as a spiculated mass, architectural distortion, or clustered microcalcifications, prompting further diagnostic imaging or biopsy. These findings are often subtle and require expert interpretation.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American College of Radiology (ACR) and American Cancer Society (ACS) recommend annual screening mammography starting at age 40 for women of average risk. The USPSTF (2023) recommends biennial screening from 40-74.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 20 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 30 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 40 years | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 50 years | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 40 years** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
