    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Comedo DCIS: Necrosis in ducts, calcifications on mammograms.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that the comedo growth pattern is a characteristic feature of a specific, high-grade subtype of Ductal Carcinoma In-Situ (DCIS). This pattern is defined by malignant epithelial cells filling the ducts with central necrosis, which often leads to calcifications.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nComedo DCIS represents a high-grade form of DCIS, characterized by solid sheets of malignant epithelial cells filling and distending the mammary ducts. The hallmark feature is central necrosis, which can be extensive and often leads to microcalcifications detectable on mammography. This necrotic debris, resembling toothpaste squeezed from a tube, gives rise to the 'comedo' (blackhead) appearance, indicating a more aggressive biological behavior within the ductal system.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Medullary carcinoma is a distinct subtype of invasive breast cancer characterized by syncytial growth, prominent lymphocytic infiltrate, and pushing borders, not a comedo pattern.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lobular carcinoma in-situ (LCIS) is a proliferation of small, uniform cells within lobules and terminal ducts, typically lacking central necrosis or a comedo pattern. It is often considered a risk factor rather than a true carcinoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Infiltrating lobular carcinoma is characterized by small, discohesive cells infiltrating in single files ('Indian file' pattern) or targetoid patterns, and does not exhibit a comedo growth pattern.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Ductal Carcinoma In-Situ (Comedo) | Lobular Carcinoma In-Situ | Infiltrating Ductal Carcinoma (NOS) | Infiltrating Lobular Carcinoma |\n|---------------------|-----------------------------------|---------------------------|-------------------------------------|--------------------------------|\n| Growth Pattern      | Ductal filling, central necrosis  | Lobular, discohesive cells | Ductal, irregular masses            | Single file, targetoid         |\n| Calcifications      | Common, often extensive           | Rare                      | Variable                            | Rare                           |\n| Palpable Mass       | Less common                       | Rare                      | Common                              | Less common, diffuse           |\n| E-cadherin          | Positive                          | Negative                  | Positive                            | Negative                       |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Comedo necrosis + DCIS = high-grade ductal disease.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, comedo DCIS often presents as pleomorphic, linear, or branching microcalcifications, which are highly suspicious for malignancy and warrant biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 3.2023). They recommend surgical excision for DCIS, often with clear margins, and may consider radiation therapy depending on risk factors.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ductal carcinoma in-situ | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Medullary carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lobular carcinoma in-situ | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Infiltrating lobular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Ductal carcinoma in-situ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
