    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 NPI: Size matters, but only 0.2 times!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe Nottingham Prognostic Index (NPI) is a critical tool for assessing prognosis in breast cancer patients. The correct formula, as indicated by the answer, accurately weights tumor size, histological grade, and nodal status to provide a prognostic score.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe NPI is a robust prognostic indicator that combines three independent variables: tumor size (measured in cm), histological grade (1-3), and nodal status (0 for negative, 1 for 1-3 nodes, 2 for 4-9 nodes, 3 for >9 nodes). The formula I = (0.2 x size) + grade + nodes assigns a specific weight to tumor size, reflecting its impact on prognosis relative to grade and nodal involvement. A lower NPI score generally correlates with a better prognosis, guiding adjuvant therapy decisions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): This option uses an incorrect coefficient of 0.4 for tumor size, which is not part of the validated Nottingham Prognostic Index formula.\nOption C (Incorrect): This option uses an incorrect coefficient of 0.6 for tumor size, deviating from the established NPI calculation.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option uses an incorrect coefficient of 0.8 for tumor size, which would significantly misrepresent the prognostic value of tumor size in the NPI.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Index | Components | Purpose | Key Coefficient for Size |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Nottingham Prognostic Index (NPI) | Tumor Size, Histological Grade, Nodal Status | Predicts long-term survival in breast cancer | 0.2 |\n| TNM Staging | Tumor Size, Nodal Involvement, Metastasis | Anatomical extent of disease, guides treatment | N/A (size is a direct T-stage component) |\n| Oncotype DX | Gene Expression Profile | Predicts recurrence risk and chemotherapy benefit | N/A (molecular) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: NPI's size coefficient is 0.2 – remember the 'two' in NottinghAm.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nTumor size is typically assessed pre-operatively via mammography, ultrasound, or MRI, and confirmed intraoperatively by palpation or post-excision pathology. Nodal status is determined by sentinel lymph node biopsy or axillary dissection, while histological grade is a pathology finding.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (latest version) recommend using prognostic tools like NPI, alongside TNM staging and molecular markers, to stratify risk and guide adjuvant therapy decisions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | I = (0.2 x size) + grade + nodes(MHSSMCET 2008) | ✅ Correct |\n| B | I = (0.4 x size) + grade + nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | I = (0.6 x size) + grade + nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | I = (0.8 x size) + grade + nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) I = (0.2 x size) + grade + nodes(MHSSMCET 2008)** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
