    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Comedo DCIS: Necrosis in the ducts, calcifications on the facts!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the type of breast carcinoma characterized by a comedo growth pattern. Ductal Carcinoma In Situ (DCIS), specifically its high-grade subtype, is classically associated with this distinctive pattern, making it the correct answer.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nComedo DCIS is a high-grade subtype of Ductal Carcinoma In Situ, characterized by malignant epithelial cells filling and distending the ducts, with prominent central necrosis. This necrosis often leads to the formation of coarse, pleomorphic calcifications and gives the appearance of 'comedones' or 'blackheads' when the necrotic material is expressed from the ducts. Histologically, it exhibits high nuclear pleomorphism and mitotic activity. Identifying comedo DCIS is crucial as it represents a more aggressive form of DCIS with a higher propensity for recurrence and progression to invasive carcinoma if not adequately treated.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Medullary carcinoma is a rare, invasive carcinoma characterized by a syncytial growth pattern, prominent lymphocytic infiltrate, and a pushing border, without a comedo pattern.\nOption C (Incorrect): Lobular carcinoma in-situ (LCIS) is characterized by small, uniform cells filling and expanding lobules and terminal ducts, typically without central necrosis or a comedo pattern. It is often considered a risk indicator rather than an obligate precursor.\nOption D (Incorrect): Infiltrating lobular carcinoma is an invasive carcinoma characterized by small, discohesive cells infiltrating in single files ('Indian file' pattern) or targetoid patterns, and does not exhibit a comedo growth pattern.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Comedo DCIS | Non-Comedo DCIS (e.g., Cribriform, Micropapillary) | Invasive Lobular Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Grade | High | Low to Intermediate | Variable, often low-grade |\n| Necrosis | Present (central) | Absent or minimal | Absent |\n| Calcifications | Often prominent, coarse, linear | Fine, granular, or absent | Rare |\n| Nuclear Pleomorphism | High | Low to moderate | Low |\n| Growth Pattern | Ductal filling with central necrosis | Ductal filling (cribriform, papillary) | Single file, targetoid |\n| E-cadherin | Positive | Positive | Negative (loss of expression) |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Comedo DCIS = high-grade DCIS with central necrosis and suspicious calcifications.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn mammography, comedo DCIS typically presents as pleomorphic, linear, or branching microcalcifications, which are highly suspicious for malignancy. Intraoperatively, if the lesion is palpable or visible on cut section, the necrotic material might be expressed from the ducts, resembling toothpaste.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the diagnosis, staging, and treatment of DCIS, including high-grade subtypes like comedo DCIS, emphasizing surgical excision with clear margins.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Ductal carcinoma in-situ | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Medullary carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Lobular carcinoma in-situ | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Infiltrating lobular carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Ductal carcinoma in-situ** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
