    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When the nipple weeps red, think papilloma ahead!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Nipple discharge. Large duct papillomas are benign epithelial proliferations within the major lactiferous ducts, often presenting with spontaneous, serous, or bloody nipple discharge due to their friable nature and location. This symptom is highly characteristic and often the sole presenting complaint.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nIntraductal papillomas, particularly those in large ducts, are typically solitary and located near the nipple. Their frond-like epithelial projections are delicate and prone to microtrauma or torsion within the duct, leading to bleeding and subsequent discharge. The discharge can be clear, serous, or bloody, and is often unilateral and spontaneous, distinguishing it from other causes of nipple discharge.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): While some papillomas can present as a palpable mass, especially if larger or associated with cysts, nipple discharge is the most characteristic and often the first sign of a large duct papilloma. A discrete mass is less common than discharge.\nOption C (Incorrect): Skin excoriation around the nipple is typically associated with chronic irritation from persistent discharge, often seen in conditions like Paget's disease or severe eczema, not a primary sign of the papilloma itself.\nOption D (Incorrect): Large duct papillomas are benign lesions. Lymph node involvement indicates malignancy (e.g., invasive carcinoma), which is not a feature of a simple papilloma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Intraductal Papilloma | Ductal Ectasia | Invasive Carcinoma | Paget's Disease |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------- | :-------------- | :----------------- | :-------------- |\n| **Discharge Type** | Serous, bloody | Green, brown | Bloody, serous | Bloody, serous |\n| **Laterality** | Unilateral | Bilateral | Unilateral | Unilateral |\n| **Spontaneity** | Spontaneous | Expressible | Spontaneous | Spontaneous |\n| **Associated Mass** | Rare | Common | Common | Rare |\n| **Pain** | Usually absent | Common | Variable | Itching, burning |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Unilateral, spontaneous, bloody nipple discharge often points to an intraductal papilloma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography may be normal or show a dilated duct. Ultrasound can reveal an intraductal mass or dilated duct. Ductography (galactography) is key, showing a filling defect within a dilated duct. Intraoperatively, excision of the involved duct will reveal the friable lesion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBS) Consensus Guideline on the Management of Benign Breast Disease (2018). Recommends excision for symptomatic papillomas or those with atypical features.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Nipple discharge | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Breast mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Skin excoriation | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Lymphnode involvement | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Nipple discharge** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
