    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't mistake Paget's for eczema; it's a unilateral red flag for cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the statement that is *not* true regarding Paget's disease of the breast. The correct answer, 'Usually bilateral,' is indeed false, as Paget's disease of the breast is overwhelmingly a unilateral condition.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPaget's disease of the breast is a rare form of breast cancer characterized by eczematous changes of the nipple and areola. It almost always indicates an underlying ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) or invasive breast cancer, which is typically confined to one breast. The malignant cells (Paget cells) migrate from the underlying ductal carcinoma to the epidermis of the nipple, causing the characteristic skin changes. Its unilateral presentation is a key distinguishing feature from benign dermatological conditions.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 'Associated intraductal carcinoma' is true. Paget's disease is nearly always associated with an underlying DCIS or invasive carcinoma, which is the source of the Paget cells.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Prognosis good in absence of lump' is true. The prognosis for Paget's disease is primarily determined by the underlying breast cancer. If there is no palpable mass, it often indicates a less advanced underlying carcinoma (e.g., DCIS without invasion), leading to a better prognosis.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'Treatment simple mastectomy with axillary clearance' is true. While breast-conserving surgery with radiation is an option for select cases, simple mastectomy with sentinel lymph node biopsy or axillary clearance remains a common and appropriate treatment, especially if there's an underlying invasive component or extensive DCIS.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Paget's Disease of Breast | Eczema of Nipple | Inflammatory Breast Cancer |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Appearance** | Unilateral, eczematous, crusting, ulceration, nipple erosion | Bilateral, itchy, dry, scaly, well-demarcated | Diffuse erythema, edema, peau d'orange, warmth |\n| **Underlying Pathology** | Almost always associated with DCIS or invasive carcinoma | Inflammatory skin condition, no malignancy | Invasive ductal carcinoma with dermal lymphatic invasion |\n| **Nipple Involvement** | Nipple often eroded/destroyed | Nipple usually spared, but can be involved | Nipple retraction/flattening possible, but not primary lesion |\n| **Prognosis** | Depends on underlying carcinoma; good if no palpable mass | Excellent, resolves with treatment | Poor, aggressive |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Paget's of breast is unilateral and signals underlying cancer.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nMammography or MRI often reveals an underlying mass or microcalcifications in the breast parenchyma. Intraoperatively, the nipple-areola complex may appear eroded or ulcerated, and a biopsy confirms the presence of Paget cells.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 3.2023). These guidelines recommend comprehensive evaluation for underlying breast cancer and appropriate surgical management based on the extent of disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Usually bilateral | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Associated intraductal carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Prognosis good in absence of lump | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Treatment simple mastectomy with axillary clearance | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Usually bilateral** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
