    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Fibroadenoma: The breast mouse that moves around.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nFibroadenomas are benign breast tumors characterized by their well-circumscribed nature and lack of invasion, which allows them to move freely within the breast tissue. This mobility, often described as a 'breast mouse,' is a key diagnostic feature distinguishing them from malignant lesions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFibroadenomas are biphasic tumors composed of both epithelial and stromal elements. Their encapsulation and lack of adherence to surrounding tissues contribute to their characteristic mobility. They typically present as a single, firm, rubbery, non-tender, and highly mobile lump, making them easily palpable and distinct from the surrounding breast parenchyma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Fixed masses are more characteristic of malignant lesions, which infiltrate and adhere to surrounding tissues. \nOption B (Incorrect): Diffuse masses suggest a more widespread process like fibrocystic changes or inflammatory conditions, not a discrete fibroadenoma. \nOption C (Incorrect): While multiple fibroadenomas can occur, the classic presentation and the most defining characteristic is a solitary, well-defined, mobile mass. 'Diffuse' is also an incorrect descriptor for a fibroadenoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Fibroadenoma | Breast Cyst | Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Mobility | Mobile ('breast mouse') | Mobile | Fixed, irregular |\n| Consistency | Rubbery, firm | Smooth, soft/firm (fluid-filled) | Hard, gritty |\n| Tenderness | Non-tender | Often tender | Non-tender (usually) |\n| Borders | Well-defined | Well-defined | Irregular, ill-defined |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A mobile breast lump in a young woman is often a fibroadenoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a fibroadenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, oval, hypoechoic mass with a smooth capsule and posterior acoustic enhancement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican College of Radiology (ACR) BI-RADS Atlas (2013): Provides standardized reporting for breast imaging, classifying fibroadenomas typically as BI-RADS 2 (benign) or 3 (probably benign).\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Fixed mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Diffuse mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Multiple diffuse mass | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Solitary mobile mass | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Solitary mobile mass** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
