    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Don't take the whole breast for a benign fibroadenoma!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Fibroadenoma. Simple mastectomy is a surgical procedure involving the removal of the entire breast tissue, typically performed for malignant or high-risk benign conditions. A fibroadenoma, being a common, benign breast tumor, does not typically warrant a simple mastectomy.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSimple mastectomy is indicated for conditions such as multi-centric breast cancer, large unifocal cancers not amenable to breast-conserving surgery, extensive ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS), inflammatory breast cancer, or as a prophylactic measure in high-risk individuals. The goal is complete removal of all breast glandular tissue to eradicate or prevent malignancy. For benign lesions like fibroadenomas, less invasive procedures such as excisional biopsy or lumpectomy are usually sufficient, often performed for diagnostic purposes or if the lesion is symptomatic or rapidly growing.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Paget's disease of the breast is a rare form of breast cancer involving the nipple and areola, often associated with underlying ductal carcinoma in situ (DCIS) or invasive breast cancer. It is a malignant condition and is therefore suitable for simple mastectomy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Cystosarcoma phyllodes (or phyllodes tumor) is a fibroepithelial tumor that can be benign, borderline, or malignant. Due to its potential for rapid growth, local recurrence, and in some cases, metastasis, wide local excision with clear margins or mastectomy (simple mastectomy) is often indicated, especially for larger or malignant variants.\nOption D (Incorrect): This option is incorrect because fibroadenoma is indeed an exception to conditions suitable for simple mastectomy.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Nature | Typical Management | Indication for Mastectomy |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Fibroadenoma | Benign | Excisional biopsy/Observation | Rarely, if very large or rapidly growing, but not standard | \n| Paget's Disease | Malignant | Mastectomy or breast-conserving surgery + radiation | Yes, standard treatment for underlying cancer | \n| Phyllodes Tumor | Benign/Borderline/Malignant | Wide local excision/Mastectomy | Yes, especially for large, recurrent, or malignant tumors | \n| DCIS (extensive) | Pre-malignant | Mastectomy or lumpectomy + radiation | Yes, if extensive or multifocal |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Simple mastectomy is for cancer or high-risk lesions, not typically for benign fibroadenomas.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a fibroadenoma typically appears as a well-circumscribed, oval, hypoechoic mass with a smooth contour. Intraoperatively, it is a firm, rubbery, mobile mass that 'shells out' easily from the surrounding breast tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (e.g., NCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology – Breast Cancer, Version 3.2023) outline indications for mastectomy, primarily focusing on malignant or high-risk conditions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Pagets disease | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Fibroadenoma | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Cystosarcoma phyllodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | None | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Fibroadenoma** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
