    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When a single duct bleeds, microdochotomy is the precise surgical deed.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is that microdochotomy is the ideal procedure for a 50-year-old woman presenting with intermittent bloody nipple discharge from a single duct and no palpable mass. This approach is chosen because it allows for precise identification and removal of the causative ductal lesion, which is often benign but requires definitive diagnosis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMicrodochotomy, also known as microdochectomy, is a targeted surgical procedure where a fine probe is inserted into the specific discharging duct, guiding the surgeon to excise only that duct and its associated lobule. This technique is highly effective for diagnosing and treating solitary duct lesions, such as intraductal papillomas, which are the most common cause of spontaneous bloody nipple discharge. It offers both diagnostic certainty by providing tissue for histopathology and therapeutic relief, while minimizing tissue removal and preserving breast cosmesis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Cytological examination of nipple discharge has low sensitivity and a high false-negative rate for malignancy, making it an unreliable standalone diagnostic tool for bloody discharge. Observation alone is inappropriate given the potential for underlying pathology.\nOption B (Incorrect): Segmental excision (lumpectomy) is an overly aggressive approach for isolated nipple discharge without a palpable mass or a clearly defined lesion on imaging. It removes more healthy breast tissue than necessary and does not specifically target the affected duct.\nOption D (Incorrect): Simple mastectomy is a radical and disfiguring procedure that is entirely inappropriate for isolated nipple discharge without a confirmed widespread malignancy or high-risk genetic predisposition.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Bloody Nipple Discharge (Solitary Duct) | Bloody Nipple Discharge (Multiple Ducts) | Non-Bloody Nipple Discharge |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Common Causes** | Intraductal papilloma, duct ectasia, carcinoma | Carcinoma, duct ectasia | Duct ectasia, fibrocystic changes, medications, pituitary adenoma |\n| **Workup** | Mammogram, ultrasound, MRI, ductography, microdochotomy | Mammogram, ultrasound, MRI, ductography, central duct excision | Mammogram, ultrasound, prolactin/TSH levels, clinical observation |\n| **Management** | Microdochotomy (diagnostic & therapeutic) | Central duct excision or targeted excision if lesion identified | Observation, medical management, or excision if persistent/atypical |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Bloody nipple discharge from a single duct without a mass warrants microdochotomy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ductography, a filling defect or obstruction within a single duct would be seen. Intraoperatively, a fine probe would be inserted into the discharging duct, guiding the surgeon to the specific duct to be excised.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) Consensus Guideline on Nipple Discharge (2016, updated 2021). It recommends targeted excision of the involved duct for persistent, spontaneous, bloody, or serosanguinous nipple discharge.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Cytological examination of discharge and if no malignant cells, to be kept  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Segmental excision of breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Microdochotomy | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Simple mastectomy | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Microdochotomy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
