    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Tylectomy: It's not just a lump, it's a 'tylos' you're taking out!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Tylectomy, derived from Greek roots, literally means the excision of a lump. This term is often used interchangeably with lumpectomy, particularly in the context of breast surgery.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe term 'tylectomy' comes from the Greek 'tylos' (lump or callus) and 'ektome' (excision). This precise etymology directly translates to the removal of a localized mass or lump, distinguishing it from more extensive resections. In surgical practice, it refers to the removal of a palpable or imaging-detected lesion while preserving surrounding healthy tissue, a common procedure in breast conservation surgery.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Excision of LN refers to lymphadenectomy, which is the removal of lymph nodes, a distinct procedure from tylectomy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Excision of breast is a mastectomy, a much more extensive procedure involving the removal of the entire breast, not just a lump.\nOption D (Incorrect): Excision of skin is a dermatological procedure, often termed an excisional biopsy or skin lesion removal, which is not what tylectomy means.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Term | Literal Meaning | Common Application |\n|---|---|---|\n| Tylectomy | Excision of a lump | Breast conservation surgery |\n| Mastectomy | Excision of the breast | Breast cancer treatment |\n| Lymphadenectomy | Excision of lymph nodes | Staging/treatment of various cancers |\n| Biopsy | Excision for examination | Diagnostic procedure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Know your Greek and Latin roots for surgical terms.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a tylectomy involves identifying and excising a discrete mass, often guided by palpation, wire localization, or intraoperative ultrasound, ensuring clear margins while minimizing removal of healthy tissue.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Guidelines for Breast Cancer (2023) recommend tylectomy (lumpectomy) as a primary surgical option for early-stage breast cancer, often followed by radiation therapy.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Excision of a lump | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Excision of LN | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Excision of breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Excision of skin | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Excision of a lump** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
