    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Axilla: where extra breasts love to reside.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is A. Axilla. This question tests fundamental knowledge regarding the embryological development and common presentation of accessory breast tissue, also known as polymastia.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nAccessory breast tissue develops along the embryonic milk line, which extends from the axilla to the groin. While it can theoretically occur anywhere along this line, the axilla is by far the most common site due to the persistence of mammary ridge tissue in this region. This tissue can undergo hormonal changes similar to normal breast tissue, leading to swelling, pain, or even lactation during pregnancy or menstruation, and carries the same risk of pathology, including malignancy.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Groin is along the milk line but is a much less common site for accessory breast tissue compared to the axilla. \nOption C (Incorrect): Buttock is not along the embryonic milk line, making it an extremely rare and atypical site for accessory breast tissue. \nOption D (Incorrect): Thigh is not along the embryonic milk line, making it an extremely rare and atypical site for accessory breast tissue.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Description | Common Location | Clinical Significance |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Polymastia | Presence of accessory breast tissue with glandular elements | Axilla (most common), inframammary fold, vulva | Can undergo hormonal changes, risk of malignancy |\n| Polythelia | Presence of accessory nipple(s) without glandular tissue | Anywhere along the milk line, often chest/abdomen | Usually asymptomatic, cosmetic concern |\n| Amastia | Absence of breast tissue | Unilateral or bilateral chest | Congenital anomaly, often associated with Poland syndrome |\n| Athelia | Absence of nipple | Unilateral or bilateral chest | Rare congenital anomaly |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: The axilla is the accessory breast's favorite address.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (mammography, ultrasound, MRI), accessory breast tissue in the axilla typically appears as glandular tissue with ducts, similar to normal breast parenchyma, often with a fatty hilum. Intraoperatively, it presents as a discrete lobulated mass of glandular and fatty tissue, sometimes encapsulated, located subcutaneously in the axillary tail region.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThere are no specific society guidelines solely dedicated to accessory breast tissue. Management generally follows principles for benign breast disease, as outlined by organizations like the American Society of Breast Surgeons (ASBrS) or the National Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) for breast cancer screening and diagnosis, if malignancy is suspected.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Axilla | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Groin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Buttock | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Thigh | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Axilla** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
