    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Blue dye: the surgeon's visual guide to the sentinel node's hide.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks about the intraoperative method for detecting sentinel lymph nodes in the axilla. Isosulfan blue dye is a classic and effective agent used to visually identify the lymphatic drainage pathway to the sentinel node.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nWhen injected peritumorally, isosulfan blue dye is absorbed by lymphatic capillaries and travels to the first draining lymph node(s), known as the sentinel node(s). The surgeon can then visually identify the blue-stained lymphatic channels and the blue-stained sentinel node(s) in the axilla. This visual guidance allows for targeted excision of these critical nodes, which are then sent for pathological evaluation to determine the presence of metastatic disease, thereby accurately staging the cancer and guiding further treatment decisions, particularly in breast cancer and melanoma.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Mammography is an imaging technique used for breast cancer screening and diagnosis, not for intraoperative lymphatic mapping or sentinel node detection.\nOption C (Incorrect): MRI (Magnetic Resonance Imaging) is a diagnostic imaging modality providing detailed soft tissue visualization, but it does not directly visualize lymphatic flow or sentinel nodes intraoperatively.\nOption D (Incorrect): CT (Computed Tomography) is a cross-sectional imaging technique primarily used for cancer staging and detecting distant metastases, not for intraoperative sentinel lymph node identification.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Method | Mechanism | Advantages | Disadvantages |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Isosulfan Blue Dye** | Visual staining of lymphatics/nodes | Simple, inexpensive, immediate visual feedback | Allergic reactions, skin/urine discoloration, less sensitive than radioisotope |\n| **Technetium-99m Sulfur Colloid** | Gamma probe detection of radioactive tracer | Highly sensitive, objective, can detect non-blue nodes | Requires nuclear medicine, radiation exposure, delayed results |\n| **Indocyanine Green (ICG) Fluorescence** | Near-infrared fluorescence imaging | Real-time visualization, high sensitivity, no radiation | Requires specialized camera, cost, limited depth penetration |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Blue dye or radioisotope for sentinel node, imaging for staging.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the operating room, after peritumoral injection, the surgeon observes blue-stained lymphatic channels leading to one or more blue-stained lymph nodes in the axilla, which are then meticulously excised.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNCCN Clinical Practice Guidelines in Oncology (NCCN Guidelines®) for Breast Cancer (e.g., Version 1.2024). These guidelines recommend sentinel lymph node biopsy for clinically node-negative breast cancer patients, often utilizing both blue dye and radioisotope for optimal detection.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Mammography | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Isosulfan blue dye | ✅ Correct |\n| C | MRI | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | CT | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Isosulfan blue dye** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
