    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 No palpable nodes? SLNB is your guide to the axilla's fate!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is B. Sentinel lymph node biopsy (SLNB) is a crucial staging procedure in early breast cancer, primarily indicated when the axillary lymph nodes are clinically negative, meaning they are not palpable.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSLNB aims to identify the first lymph node(s) to which cancer cells are most likely to spread from the primary tumor. By injecting a tracer (dye, radioisotope, or both) near the tumor, surgeons can locate and remove these sentinel nodes for pathological examination. This minimally invasive approach allows for accurate axillary staging while avoiding the morbidity of a full axillary lymph node dissection (ALND) in patients with negative sentinel nodes, thereby reducing risks like lymphedema.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): If lymph nodes are clinically palpable, they are considered suspicious for metastasis. In such cases, a fine needle aspiration (FNA) or core needle biopsy of the palpable node is typically performed to confirm metastasis. If positive, ALND or neoadjuvant chemotherapy followed by ALND is often indicated, and SLNB may not be necessary or appropriate as the primary staging tool.\nOption C (Incorrect): Similar to option A, a palpable axillary node suggests clinical involvement. The standard approach would be to biopsy the palpable node directly rather than performing an SLNB, which is designed for clinically node-negative patients.\nOption D (Incorrect): If breast cancer is already metastatic (e.g., to distant organs), the primary focus shifts to systemic therapy. While axillary staging might still be performed in some contexts, SLNB is not the primary indication for a patient with known distant metastasis, as the prognosis is already determined by the systemic spread.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Clinical Axillary Status | Recommended Axillary Management | Rationale |\n| :----------------------- | :------------------------------- | :-------- |\n| Clinically Node-Negative | Sentinel Lymph Node Biopsy (SLNB) | To accurately stage the axilla with minimal morbidity, avoiding full ALND if sentinel nodes are negative. |\n| Clinically Node-Positive | Biopsy of palpable node (FNA/core biopsy) followed by ALND or Neoadjuvant Chemotherapy | To confirm metastasis and guide definitive axillary treatment, as SLNB may have a higher false-negative rate in this setting. |\n| Known Distant Metastasis | Systemic therapy is primary; axillary surgery individualized | Axillary staging is less critical for prognosis; focus is on systemic disease control. |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: SLNB is for clinically node-negative breast cancer to avoid unnecessary ALND.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, a blue dye (e.g., Isosulfan blue or Methylene blue) and/or a radioactive tracer (e.g., Technetium-99m sulfur colloid) are injected. The surgeon uses a gamma probe to detect radioactivity and visually identifies blue-stained lymphatic channels leading to the sentinel node(s).\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nNational Comprehensive Cancer Network (NCCN) Guidelines for Breast Cancer (latest version, e.g., 2023). These guidelines recommend SLNB for patients with clinically node-negative invasive breast cancer.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | LN palpable | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Breast mass but no lymph node palpable | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Breast lump with palpable axillary node | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Metastatic CA breast | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Breast mass but no lymph node palpable** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
