    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 I-131: The thyroid's kryptonite, selectively zapping cancer cells!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question assesses knowledge of targeted radionuclide therapy for differentiated thyroid cancer (DTC). The correct answer, I-131, is the cornerstone for adjuvant therapy post-thyroidectomy due to the unique iodine-concentrating ability of thyroid cells.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDifferentiated thyroid cancer cells, including papillary and follicular types, retain the ability to uptake iodine via the sodium-iodide symporter (NIS). I-131, a radioactive isotope of iodine, is selectively absorbed by these cells. Once inside, it emits beta particles, which have a short path length, delivering a high dose of radiation directly to the cancerous cells while sparing surrounding healthy tissue. This targeted radiation destroys residual thyroid tissue and metastatic foci, improving patient outcomes.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): 99mTc (Technetium-99m) is primarily used for diagnostic imaging (e.g., thyroid scans, bone scans) due to its gamma emission, not for therapeutic ablation.\nOption C (Incorrect): P-32 (Phosphorus-32) is a beta-emitter used in the treatment of polycythemia vera and bone metastases, but it does not specifically target thyroid tissue.\nOption D (Incorrect): I-131 MIBG (Metaiodobenzylguanidine) is used for the diagnosis and treatment of neuroendocrine tumors like pheochromocytoma and paraganglioma, as it targets adrenergic tissues, not thyroid cancer.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Radioisotope | Primary Use | Mechanism |\n|---|---|---|\n| I-131 | Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (DTC) ablation, hyperthyroidism | Beta emission, targets NIS-expressing thyroid cells |\n| 99mTc | Diagnostic imaging (thyroid scan, bone scan) | Gamma emission, short half-life |\n| P-32 | Polycythemia Vera, bone metastases | Beta emission, targets rapidly dividing cells/bone |\n| I-131 MIBG | Pheochromocytoma, Paraganglioma | Targets adrenergic tissue via norepinephrine transporter |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: I-131 for DTC is about targeted beta-radiation via NIS.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPost-I-131 ablation, a whole-body scan (WBS) is performed to detect residual thyroid tissue or metastatic disease, appearing as areas of increased radioiodine uptake.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015 (updated 2023). The ATA guidelines recommend radioactive iodine (RAI) therapy for selected patients with differentiated thyroid cancer after total or near-total thyroidectomy to ablate remnant thyroid tissue and treat known or suspected metastatic disease.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | I-131 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | 99mTc | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | P-32 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | I-131 MIBG | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) I-131** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
