    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Follicular: For bone, it's the one to fear!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Follicular thyroid carcinoma. This type of thyroid cancer is well-known for its propensity to spread hematogenously, meaning through the bloodstream, making distant sites like bone a common target for metastasis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nFollicular thyroid carcinoma (FTC) is characterized by its tendency for vascular invasion, allowing cancer cells to enter the bloodstream and travel to distant sites. Bone is a highly vascular tissue, making it a frequent site for these hematogenous metastases. These bone metastases can be osteolytic (bone-destroying) or osteoblastic (bone-forming) and often present as pain, pathological fractures, or hypercalcemia. This pattern distinguishes FTC from other thyroid cancers that primarily spread via lymphatic channels.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Papillary) (Incorrect): Papillary thyroid carcinoma primarily spreads via lymphatic channels to regional lymph nodes in the neck. While distant metastases can occur, bone involvement is less common than with follicular carcinoma, and lung is a more frequent site for distant spread.\nOption C (Hurthle cell tumour) (Incorrect): Hurthle cell carcinoma is considered a variant of follicular thyroid carcinoma. While it also has a propensity for hematogenous spread and can metastasize to bone, follicular carcinoma is the broader category and the most common type primarily associated with bone metastasis.\nOption D (Anaplastic) (Incorrect): Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma is an extremely aggressive and rapidly growing tumor. It typically presents with extensive local invasion and often metastasizes early to lungs and other soft tissues. Patients often succumb to local disease or lung metastases before widespread bone metastases become a dominant clinical feature, although it can occur.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Thyroid Cancer Type | Common Metastatic Spread | Key Features |\n| :------------------ | :----------------------- | :----------- |\n| Papillary           | Lymphatic (regional nodes) | Most common type, good prognosis, often multifocal |\n| Follicular          | Hematogenous (bone, lung) | Second most common, capsular/vascular invasion, iodine avid |\n| Medullary           | Lymphatic & Hematogenous (nodes, liver, lung, bone) | Arises from parafollicular C-cells, associated with MEN2, calcitonin marker |\n| Anaplastic          | Local invasion, Hematogenous (lung, soft tissue) | Rarest, most aggressive, poor prognosis, rapid growth |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Follicular thyroid cancer loves bone.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (e.g., bone scan, CT, MRI), bone metastases from follicular thyroid cancer often appear as osteolytic or mixed lytic/blastic lesions, sometimes with pathological fractures. They can be avid on iodine scans if differentiated.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines (e.g., 2015 or later): These guidelines provide comprehensive recommendations for the management of differentiated thyroid cancer, including surveillance for distant metastases and treatment strategies for bone involvement.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follicular | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Papillary (AIIMS Nov 99) | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hurthle cell tumour | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Anaplastic | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Follicular** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
