    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hurthle cells: follicular variant, invasion is the key!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThis question assesses your understanding of thyroid cancer pathology, specifically the classification of Hurthle cell tumors. The correct answer is Follicular carcinoma thyroid, as Hurthle cell tumors are now considered a variant of follicular neoplasms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHurthle cells, also known as oxyphilic cells, are characterized by abundant granular eosinophilic cytoplasm due to a high density of mitochondria. While they can be found in benign adenomas, when malignant, they are classified as a variant of follicular carcinoma. The diagnosis of malignancy in Hurthle cell neoplasms, like conventional follicular neoplasms, relies on the demonstration of capsular or vascular invasion, as nuclear features alone are not sufficient for diagnosis.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Papillary carcinoma thyroid is the most common type, characterized by distinct nuclear features (e.g., Orphan Annie eye nuclei, nuclear grooves, pseudoinclusions) and often psammoma bodies, not Hurthle cells.\nOption C (Incorrect): Medullary carcinoma thyroid originates from parafollicular C-cells and secretes calcitonin, distinct from follicular cell-derived tumors.\nOption D (Incorrect): Anaplastic carcinoma is a highly aggressive, undifferentiated thyroid cancer with a very poor prognosis, lacking the specific Hurthle cell morphology.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature           | Papillary Carcinoma       | Follicular Carcinoma      | Medullary Carcinoma       | Anaplastic Carcinoma       |\n|-------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------|---------------------------|----------------------------|\n| **Origin**        | Follicular cells          | Follicular cells          | Parafollicular C-cells    | Undifferentiated follicular|\n| **Histology**     | Orphan Annie nuclei, psammoma bodies | Follicular architecture, capsular/vascular invasion | Amyloid, neuroendocrine granules | Pleomorphic, giant cells, spindle cells |\n| **Hurthle Cells** | Rare                      | Can be a variant          | No                        | No                         |\n| **Prognosis**     | Excellent                 | Good                      | Variable                  | Very Poor                  |\n| **Metastasis**    | Lymphatic                 | Hematogenous              | Lymphatic & Hematogenous  | Local & Distant            |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Hurthle cell tumors are follicular neoplasms; invasion defines malignancy.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, Hurthle cell carcinomas may appear as solid, hypoechoic nodules, often with irregular margins. Intraoperatively, they typically present as a solitary nodule, indistinguishable from other follicular neoplasms until definitive histopathology confirms capsular or vascular invasion.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines 2015: These guidelines classify Hurthle cell carcinoma as a variant of follicular thyroid carcinoma and provide recommendations for its management, emphasizing the need for surgical resection and risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Papillary carcinoma thyroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Follicular carcinoma thyroid | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Medullary carcinoma thyroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Anaplastic carcinoma | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Follicular carcinoma thyroid** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
