    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Amyloid in thyroid cancer means Medullary, always.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the type of thyroid carcinoma characterized by amyloid deposition. The correct answer is Medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC). This is a key distinguishing feature of MTC, which originates from parafollicular C-cells.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMedullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) is unique among thyroid malignancies as it arises from the neuroendocrine parafollicular C-cells, not the follicular cells. These C-cells secrete calcitonin, which can polymerize and deposit as amyloid within the tumor stroma. This amyloid, identifiable by Congo red staining with apple-green birefringence under polarized light, is a pathognomonic histological feature that differentiates MTC from other thyroid cancers.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Follicular carcinoma originates from follicular cells and does not exhibit amyloid deposition. It is characterized by capsular and/or vascular invasion.\nOption B (Incorrect): Papillary carcinoma, also of follicular cell origin, is identified by distinctive nuclear features (e.g., Orphan Annie eye nuclei, nuclear grooves, pseudoinclusions) and psammoma bodies, not amyloid.\nOption C (Incorrect): Anaplastic carcinoma is a highly aggressive, undifferentiated tumor of follicular cell origin. It lacks specific features like amyloid and is characterized by pleomorphic cells and rapid growth.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Medullary Carcinoma | Papillary Carcinoma | Follicular Carcinoma | Anaplastic Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Cell Origin | Parafollicular C-cells | Follicular cells | Follicular cells | Follicular cells |\n| Amyloid Deposition | Yes (calcitonin-derived) | No | No | No |\n| Tumor Marker | Calcitonin, CEA | Thyroglobulin | Thyroglobulin | None specific |\n| Genetic Mutation | RET proto-oncogene | BRAF, RET/PTC | RAS, PAX8/PPARγ | TP53, BRAF |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Medullary thyroid cancer = C-cells + Calcitonin + Congo Red (Amyloid).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn histopathology, a Congo red stain of the tumor will show apple-green birefringence under polarized light, confirming the presence of amyloid. Intraoperatively, MTC may appear as a firm, often solitary nodule, and regional lymph node involvement (central and lateral neck) is common.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015 or later). These guidelines highlight the importance of calcitonin measurement in the evaluation of thyroid nodules and recognize amyloid deposition as a diagnostic feature of MTC.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follicular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Papillary | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Anaplastic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Medullary | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Medullary** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
