    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When amyloid appears, think MTC; total thyroidectomy and neck dissection is the key.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe presence of amyloid in a thyroid nodule biopsy is pathognomonic for Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (MTC). MTC is known for its propensity for early lymphatic spread, making a palpable cervical lymph node a significant finding. Therefore, the treatment must address both the primary tumor and potential nodal metastases.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMedullary thyroid carcinoma originates from the parafollicular C-cells and secretes calcitonin. Its aggressive nature and high rate of regional lymph node metastasis necessitate a total thyroidectomy to remove all C-cell tissue and a therapeutic modified neck dissection for clinically involved nodes. This comprehensive approach aims for complete surgical clearance and improved long-term survival.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): This describes a subtotal thyroidectomy or lobectomy with isthmusectomy, which is inadequate for MTC due to its multifocal potential and high risk of contralateral disease and nodal spread. The typo 'bone' instead of 'lobe' also makes it nonsensical.\nOption B (Incorrect): Similar to A, a subtotal thyroidectomy is insufficient for MTC, which requires total thyroidectomy due to its multifocal nature and the need to remove all C-cell tissue. It also doesn't specify a proper neck dissection for the palpable node.\nOption D (Incorrect): While total thyroidectomy is correct, irradiation alone is not the primary treatment for involved cervical lymph nodes in MTC. Surgical excision via neck dissection is paramount for regional control, with external beam radiation therapy typically reserved for adjuvant settings in high-risk cases or for unresectable disease.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma (PTC) | Follicular Thyroid Carcinoma (FTC) | Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (MTC) | Anaplastic Thyroid Carcinoma (ATC) |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Origin | Follicular cells | Follicular cells | Parafollicular C-cells | Dedifferentiated follicular cells |\n| Biopsy finding | Orphan Annie nuclei, psammoma bodies | Follicular architecture (requires excision for diagnosis) | Amyloid, calcitonin immunostain | Spindle/giant cells, pleomorphism |\n| Spread | Lymphatic (common) | Hematogenous (common) | Lymphatic & Hematogenous | Direct invasion, rapid spread |\n| Initial Surgery | Lobectomy or Total Thyroidectomy | Total Thyroidectomy | Total Thyroidectomy + Neck Dissection | Palliative (tracheostomy, debulking) |\n| Adjuvant Therapy | Radioactive Iodine (RAI) for high risk | RAI for most | External Beam Radiation (EBRT) for high risk/residual | EBRT, chemotherapy |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Amyloid in thyroid biopsy = Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma; treat with total thyroidectomy and neck dissection.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, MTC often appears as a solid, hypoechoic nodule with irregular margins and microcalcifications. Intraoperatively, MTC can be firm, and involved lymph nodes may be enlarged and firm, often in the central and lateral neck compartments.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015 or latest update). They recommend total thyroidectomy and central neck dissection for MTC, with therapeutic lateral neck dissection for clinically involved nodes.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Removal of the involved node, the isthmus, a portion of the opposite bone a | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Removal of the involved lobe, the isthmus, a portion of the opposite lobe,  | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Total thyroidectomy and modified neck dissection on the side of the enlarge | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Total thyroidectomy and irradiation of the cervical lymph nodes | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Total thyroidectomy and modified neck dissection on the side of the enlarged lymph node** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
