    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When pheo meets thyroid, think MEN2 and C-cells!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation with pheochromocytoma alongside a thyroid carcinoma strongly points to a syndromic association. Medullary thyroid carcinoma (MTC) is a hallmark component of Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2 (MEN2), which characteristically includes pheochromocytoma.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMEN2 is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by germline mutations in the RET proto-oncogene. MEN2A typically manifests with medullary thyroid carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism, while MEN2B includes MTC, pheochromocytoma, and mucosal neuromas/marfanoid habitus. The co-occurrence of pheochromocytoma and thyroid carcinoma in this patient is the classic presentation of MEN2, directly linking the thyroid cancer to the medullary type.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma is a highly aggressive, undifferentiated cancer, typically seen in older patients, and is not associated with pheochromocytoma or MEN syndromes.\nOption C (Incorrect): Follicular thyroid carcinoma is a differentiated thyroid cancer, often associated with iodine deficiency, and does not have a syndromic link to pheochromocytoma.\nOption D (Incorrect): Papillary thyroid carcinoma is the most common differentiated thyroid cancer, often associated with radiation exposure, but is not part of the MEN2 syndrome or linked to pheochromocytoma.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Papillary | Follicular | Medullary | Anaplastic |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Cell Origin | Follicular | Follicular | Parafollicular C-cells | Dedifferentiated |\n| Incidence | Most common | Second most common | ~5% | <2% |\n| Prognosis | Excellent | Good | Variable | Very poor |\n| Tumor Marker | Thyroglobulin | Thyroglobulin | Calcitonin, CEA | None specific |\n| Syndromic Link | No | No | MEN2 | No |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Pheochromocytoma + Thyroid cancer = Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma (MEN2).\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging, pheochromocytomas are typically hypervascular adrenal masses, often identified on CT or MRI. MTC may appear as a solid, often calcified, thyroid nodule. Intraoperatively, pheochromocytoma resection requires meticulous blood pressure control, while MTC surgery involves total thyroidectomy and often central neck dissection, with potential for lateral neck dissection if lymph nodes are involved.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015, updated 2023). These guidelines recommend genetic testing for RET mutations in all MTC patients and surveillance for other MEN2 components.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Anaplastic | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Medullary | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Follicular | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Papillary | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Medullary** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
