    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Thyroid lymphoma: rapid growth, not slow; think Hashimoto's, not benign!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the statement that is NOT true about thyroid lymphoma. The correct answer, 'slow growing,' is false because thyroid lymphoma is typically an aggressive, rapidly enlarging malignancy, often presenting with acute symptoms.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThyroid lymphoma, particularly diffuse large B-cell lymphoma (DLBCL), is characterized by rapid enlargement of the thyroid gland, often in the setting of long-standing Hashimoto's thyroiditis. This rapid growth can lead to acute compressive symptoms such as dysphagia, dyspnea, and hoarseness. Its aggressive nature and rapid progression are key distinguishing features from more indolent thyroid pathologies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 'More common in females' - This is true. Thyroid lymphoma, like its precursor Hashimoto's thyroiditis, has a significant female predominance.\nOption C (Incorrect): 'Clinically confused with undifferentiated tumors' - This is true. Anaplastic thyroid carcinoma, an undifferentiated tumor, also presents as a rapidly enlarging, firm neck mass with compressive symptoms, making clinical differentiation from lymphoma challenging without biopsy.\nOption D (Incorrect): 'May present with respiratory distress and dysphagia' - This is true. Due to its rapid growth and the confined space of the neck, thyroid lymphoma frequently causes compression of the trachea and esophagus, leading to these acute symptoms.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature                 | Thyroid Lymphoma                               | Anaplastic Thyroid Carcinoma                   | Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma                   |\n| :---------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :--------------------------------------------- | :-------------------------------------------- |\n| **Growth Rate**         | Rapidly enlarging                              | Rapidly enlarging                              | Slow growing                                  |\n| **Association**         | Hashimoto's thyroiditis                        | Often dedifferentiation from other carcinomas  | Radiation exposure, familial syndromes        |\n| **Prognosis**           | Variable, often good with treatment (chemo/RT) | Very poor                                      | Excellent                                     |\n| **Treatment**           | Chemotherapy, radiation, surgery (debulking)   | Palliative, surgery, radiation, systemic therapy | Surgery (thyroidectomy), radioactive iodine   |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Thyroid lymphoma is a rapidly growing cancer, often mistaken for anaplastic carcinoma.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn imaging (US/CT), thyroid lymphoma typically appears as a diffuse, hypoechoic, solid mass with rapid growth. Intraoperatively, it presents as a firm, infiltrative mass, often difficult to distinguish from anaplastic carcinoma without frozen section or core needle biopsy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines (e.g., 2015 or later versions) provide recommendations for the diagnosis and management of thyroid nodules and malignancies, emphasizing the role of fine-needle aspiration (FNA) or core biopsy for definitive diagnosis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | More common in females | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Slow growing | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Clinically confused with undifferentiated tumors | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | May present with respiratory distress and dysphagia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Slow growing** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
