    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Iodine-131: The thyroid's worst enemy, cancer's best friend.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is I-131. Radioactive iodine (I-131) is a cornerstone in the treatment of differentiated thyroid cancer due to the unique ability of thyroid cells to absorb iodine.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nDifferentiated thyroid cancer cells, such as papillary and follicular carcinomas, retain the iodide-concentrating mechanism found in normal thyroid cells. I-131, a beta-emitting radioisotope, is selectively taken up by these cells. Once concentrated, the beta particles emitted by I-131 cause localized cellular damage and destruction, effectively ablating residual thyroid tissue or treating metastatic disease with minimal systemic toxicity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): I-125 is primarily used in brachytherapy for localized cancers (e.g., prostate cancer) or for diagnostic imaging, not for systemic treatment of thyroid malignancy.\nOption C (Incorrect): Technetium-99m (Tc-99m) is a diagnostic radioisotope used for various imaging studies (e.g., thyroid scans, bone scans) but does not have therapeutic beta emissions for cancer treatment.\nOption D (Incorrect): Phosphorus-32 (P-32) is a beta-emitter used in some hematologic malignancies (e.g., polycythemia vera) or for palliative treatment of bone metastases, but it lacks specific affinity for thyroid tissue.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Radioisotope | Primary Use | Mechanism/Key Feature |\n|---|---|---|\n| I-131 | Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (Tx), Hyperthyroidism (Tx) | Beta emission, selective uptake by thyroid cells |\n| I-123 | Thyroid Imaging (Dx) | Gamma emission, short half-life, no therapeutic effect |\n| Tc-99m | Various Imaging (Dx) | Gamma emission, short half-life, readily available |\n| P-32 | Polycythemia Vera (Tx), Bone Mets (Palliative Tx) | Beta emission, non-specific uptake or targeted delivery |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: I-131 for thyroid cancer is like a guided missile for rogue thyroid cells.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nPost-I-131 whole-body scans are crucial to identify residual thyroid tissue or metastatic disease, appearing as areas of focal uptake. Intraoperatively, thyroid malignancies often present as firm, irregular nodules, sometimes with associated lymphadenopathy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (e.g., 2015, 2023 updates). These guidelines provide recommendations for the use of I-131 for remnant ablation and adjuvant therapy based on risk stratification.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | I-131 | ✅ Correct |\n| B | I-125 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Tc-99 | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | P-32 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) I-131** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
