    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Pregnant and hyperthyroid? PTU is your first-trimester friend!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nPropylthiouracil (PTU) is the preferred antithyroid drug for treating thyrotoxicosis during pregnancy, especially in the first trimester. This choice is based on its lower placental transfer compared to other thionamides, minimizing fetal exposure and potential teratogenic effects.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nPTU inhibits thyroid hormone synthesis by blocking the organification of iodide and the coupling of iodotyrosines. Crucially, it also inhibits the peripheral conversion of T4 to T3. Its higher protein binding and lower placental passage make it the safer option for the developing fetus during the critical first trimester, reducing the risk of congenital anomalies associated with methimazole.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Carbimazole is a prodrug that is metabolized to methimazole. Therefore, it carries the same risks as methimazole, including a higher risk of teratogenicity (e.g., aplasia cutis) when used in the first trimester.\nOption C (Incorrect): Methimazole is associated with a higher risk of congenital anomalies, particularly aplasia cutis, choanal atresia, and esophageal atresia, when administered during the first trimester of pregnancy. While it may be considered in the second and third trimesters, PTU is generally preferred for initial management.\nOption D (Incorrect): Radioactive I-131 is absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy. It crosses the placenta and can be concentrated by the fetal thyroid gland, leading to irreversible fetal hypothyroidism and cretinism.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Propylthiouracil (PTU) | Methimazole (MMI) / Carbimazole | Radioactive Iodine (I-131) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Pregnancy (1st Trimester)** | **Agent of Choice** (lower placental transfer) | Contraindicated (higher teratogenic risk: aplasia cutis, choanal/esophageal atresia) | Absolutely Contraindicated (fetal thyroid destruction) |\n| **Pregnancy (2nd/3rd Trimester)** | Can be used | Can be considered (lower teratogenic risk than 1st trimester, but PTU still preferred by some) | Absolutely Contraindicated |\n| **Mechanism** | Inhibits synthesis & peripheral T4->T3 conversion | Inhibits synthesis | Destroys thyroid tissue |\n| **Side Effects** | Liver toxicity (rare but severe), vasculitis | Agranulocytosis, cholestatic jaundice | Hypothyroidism, radiation exposure |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: For thyrotoxicosis in pregnancy, PTU is preferred in the first trimester; MMI/Carbimazole later.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a hypervascular thyroid gland with increased blood flow may be seen in thyrotoxicosis. Intraoperatively, the thyroid gland would appear enlarged and highly vascular, requiring meticulous hemostasis during thyroidectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Disease During Pregnancy and the Postpartum (2017). Recommends PTU in the first trimester due to lower teratogenic risk.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Carbimazole | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Propylthiouracil | ✅ Correct |\n| C | Methimazole | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Radioactive I-131 | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: B) Propylthiouracil** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
