    "specialty": "General Surgery",
    "difficulty": "Medium",
    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 When tetany strikes post-thyroidectomy, give calcium gluconate, not excuses!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of tetany post-thyroidectomy is a classic sign of acute hypocalcemia, most commonly due to iatrogenic parathyroid injury or removal. Immediate management requires rapid repletion of calcium, for which intravenous calcium gluconate is the gold standard.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nTetany is a severe manifestation of hypocalcemia, characterized by neuromuscular irritability resulting from decreased extracellular calcium stabilizing nerve membranes. Post-thyroidectomy, this is typically caused by transient or permanent hypoparathyroidism due to inadvertent removal or devascularization of the parathyroid glands. IV calcium gluconate provides readily available calcium to quickly raise serum calcium levels, alleviating symptoms and preventing life-threatening complications such as laryngospasm, seizures, or cardiac arrhythmias. It is preferred over calcium chloride due to less venous irritation and a lower risk of tissue necrosis if extravasation occurs.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Incorrect): Bicarbonate would worsen hypocalcemia by increasing protein binding of calcium and decreasing ionized calcium, potentially exacerbating tetany. It is used for metabolic acidosis, not hypocalcemia.\nOption C (Incorrect): Calcitonin lowers serum calcium by inhibiting osteoclast activity and increasing renal calcium excretion. Administering calcitonin would worsen hypocalcemia, making it contraindicated in this scenario.\nOption D (Incorrect): Vitamin D is crucial for long-term calcium absorption and metabolism but has a delayed onset of action. It is not suitable for the acute, emergent management of tetany, although it is vital for chronic hypocalcemia management.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Acute Hypocalcemia (Tetany) | Chronic Hypocalcemia |\n| :------------------ | :-------------------------------------------------------- | :------------------------------------------------------- |\n| **Presentation** | Tetany, paresthesias, Chvostek/Trousseau signs, seizures | Fatigue, muscle cramps, dry skin, cataracts, basal ganglia calcification |\n| **Primary Tx** | IV Calcium Gluconate | Oral Calcium + Vitamin D (Calcitriol) |\n| **Onset of Action** | Immediate | Days to weeks |\n| **Goal** | Rapid symptom relief, prevent life-threatening events | Maintain normocalcemia, prevent long-term complications |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Acute tetany post-thyroidectomy = IV calcium gluconate STAT.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIntraoperatively, parathyroid glands are typically identified as small (3-6mm), yellowish-brown, ovoid structures, often near the posterior thyroid capsule or within the thyroid parenchyma. Accidental removal or devascularization during thyroidectomy is the primary cause of post-op hypocalcemia. While hypocalcemia itself doesn't show specific imaging findings, chronic hypoparathyroidism can lead to basal ganglia calcifications on CT scans.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Management of Postoperative Hypoparathyroidism (2016). These guidelines recommend monitoring serum calcium levels post-thyroidectomy and initiating IV calcium for symptomatic hypocalcemia or severe asymptomatic hypocalcemia.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | IV calcium gluconate | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Bicarbonate | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Calcitonin | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Vitamin D | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) IV calcium gluconate** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
    "verified_answer": "A"
