    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A swollen neck after thyroidectomy is a ticking time bomb for the airway.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe verdict is respiratory obstruction. This is correct because acute neck swelling following thyroidectomy, particularly if rapidly progressive, most commonly indicates a hematoma. This hematoma can compress the trachea, leading to acute airway compromise, which is the most immediate and life-threatening complication.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nA rapidly expanding hematoma in the confined space of the neck can exert significant extrinsic pressure on the trachea. This compression can quickly lead to symptoms such as stridor, dyspnea, and ultimately complete airway obstruction. This scenario constitutes a surgical emergency requiring immediate intervention to decompress the airway and prevent catastrophic respiratory failure.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption B (Recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy) (Incorrect): While a possible complication, it primarily manifests as voice changes (hoarseness) and does not cause neck swelling or acute respiratory obstruction in the manner described.\nOption C (Hypovolemia) (Incorrect): Hypovolemia is a systemic issue related to blood loss, not typically manifested as localized neck swelling. While significant blood loss can occur, the *swelling* points to a localized collection, not systemic hypovolemia as the primary complication of the swelling.\nOption D (Hypocalcemia) (Incorrect): Hypocalcemia is a metabolic complication due to parathyroid gland injury or removal. It causes symptoms like perioral numbness, tingling, and tetany, but not neck swelling or acute respiratory obstruction. It is also typically a delayed complication.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Complication Type | Example | Onset | Key Symptom | Management |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Immediate (Surgical Emergency) | Hematoma | Hours post-op | Neck swelling, respiratory distress, stridor | Immediate surgical exploration/decompression |\n| Early (Metabolic) | Hypocalcemia | 24-72 hours post-op | Perioral numbness, tingling, tetany | Calcium/Vitamin D supplementation |\n| Early (Neurological) | Recurrent Laryngeal Nerve Palsy | Immediately to days post-op | Hoarseness, dysphonia | Observation, speech therapy, possible surgery |\n| Late | Hypothyroidism | Weeks to months post-op | Fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance | Thyroid hormone replacement |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Post-thyroidectomy neck swelling + respiratory distress = Airway emergency, open the wound!\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nIn the OR, opening the neck incision would reveal a rapidly expanding hematoma, often under tension, compressing the trachea. Imaging (CT scan) would show a large, well-defined fluid collection in the neck compressing the airway.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Guidelines for the Surgical Management of Thyroid Cancer (2019). These guidelines emphasize prompt recognition and management of post-operative complications, including hematoma and airway compromise.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Respiratory obstruction | ✅ Correct |\n| B | Recurrent laryngeal nerve palsy | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hypovolemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Hypocalcemia | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: A) Respiratory obstruction** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
