    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hashimoto's hurts follicles, Orphan Annie eyes hint at cancer.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks to identify the statement that is NOT true regarding Hashimoto's thyroiditis. Hashimoto's is an autoimmune condition characterized by chronic inflammation and destruction of the thyroid gland. Orphan Annie eye nuclei are a classic histological feature of papillary thyroid carcinoma, not Hashimoto's thyroiditis.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHashimoto's thyroiditis is an autoimmune disease where the body's immune system attacks the thyroid gland. Pathologically, this leads to extensive lymphocytic infiltration, follicular destruction, and often oncocytic metaplasia (Hurthle cell change) of the follicular cells. These changes collectively contribute to hypothyroidism. In contrast, Orphan Annie eye nuclei, characterized by optically clear, ground-glass nuclei with prominent nucleoli, are pathognomonic for papillary thyroid carcinoma, a distinct malignant entity.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Follicular destruction is a hallmark of Hashimoto's thyroiditis, as the autoimmune process targets and damages thyroid follicles.\nOption B (Incorrect): An increase in lymphocytes, specifically a dense lymphocytic infiltrate, is a defining histological feature of Hashimoto's thyroiditis.\nOption C (Incorrect): Oncocytic metaplasia, also known as Hurthle cell change, is a common finding in Hashimoto's thyroiditis, representing a compensatory change in follicular cells.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hashimoto's Thyroiditis | Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma |\n|---|---|---|\n| Etiology | Autoimmune (anti-TPO, anti-Tg antibodies) | Genetic mutations (BRAF, RET/PTC) |\n| Histology | Lymphocytic infiltrate, Hurthle cells, follicular atrophy/destruction | Orphan Annie eye nuclei, nuclear grooves, pseudoinclusions, psammoma bodies |\n| Clinical | Hypothyroidism, goiter, increased lymphoma risk | Euthyroid, palpable nodule, excellent prognosis |\n| Management | Thyroid hormone replacement | Surgery (thyroidectomy), radioactive iodine |\n\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Orphan Annie eye nuclei are for Papillary Thyroid Carcinoma, not Hashimoto's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, Hashimoto's typically presents as a diffusely enlarged, hypoechoic, and heterogeneous gland with increased vascularity. Papillary thyroid carcinoma, however, often appears as a solitary hypoechoic nodule with irregular margins, microcalcifications, and possibly abnormal lymph nodes.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2023) provide comprehensive guidance on diagnosis and management of both benign and malignant thyroid conditions.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Follicular destruction | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Increase in lymphocytes | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Oncocytic metaplasia | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | Orphan Annie eye nuclei | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) Orphan Annie eye nuclei** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
