    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Hashimoto's: The autoimmune leader of thyroiditis.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe correct answer is Hashimoto's thyroiditis. This is the most prevalent autoimmune thyroid disease and the leading cause of hypothyroidism in iodine-sufficient areas worldwide.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nHashimoto's thyroiditis, also known as chronic lymphocytic thyroiditis, is an organ-specific autoimmune disorder characterized by the destruction of thyroid follicular cells by autoantibodies and cytotoxic T lymphocytes. Key antibodies include anti-thyroid peroxidase (TPO) antibodies and anti-thyroglobulin (Tg) antibodies. This chronic inflammation leads to progressive thyroid dysfunction, often resulting in hypothyroidism and goiter.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Reidel’s thyroiditis is a rare, invasive fibrosing condition that replaces normal thyroid tissue with dense fibrous tissue, often extending to adjacent structures. It is not the most common form.\nOption B (Incorrect): Subacute thyroiditis (De Quervain's thyroiditis) is a transient inflammatory condition, often post-viral, characterized by painful thyroid enlargement and a triphasic course of thyroid function. It is less common than Hashimoto's.\nOption D (Incorrect): Viral thyroiditis is a general term, often referring to subacute thyroiditis, which is typically post-viral. While viruses can trigger thyroiditis, Hashimoto's is the most common type of thyroiditis overall, not just viral.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | Hashimoto's Thyroiditis | Subacute (De Quervain's) Thyroiditis | Riedel's Thyroiditis |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Etiology** | Autoimmune (anti-TPO, anti-Tg antibodies) | Post-viral (e.g., mumps, influenza) | Idiopathic, fibrosing process |\n| **Prevalence** | Most common thyroiditis | Less common than Hashimoto's | Very rare |\n| **Symptoms** | Often asymptomatic, hypothyroidism, goiter | Painful thyroid, fever, transient hyper/hypothyroidism | Painless, rock-hard goiter, compressive symptoms |\n| **Pathology** | Lymphocytic infiltration, Hurthle cells | Granulomatous inflammation, giant cells | Dense fibrosis, often extending beyond capsule |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: When in doubt about \"most common thyroiditis,\" think Hashimoto's.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, Hashimoto's thyroiditis typically presents with a diffusely enlarged, heterogeneous, and hypoechoic thyroid gland with increased vascularity on Doppler. Intraoperatively, the gland may appear firm and pale, with a lobulated surface.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Dysfunction (e.g., 2017) recommend screening for thyroid dysfunction in patients with symptoms suggestive of hypothyroidism and monitoring thyroid function in patients with known Hashimoto's thyroiditis.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Reidel’s thyroiditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Subacute thyroiditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Hashimoto’s thyroiditis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Viral thyroiditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Hashimoto’s thyroiditis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Easy** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
