    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Sore throat, then sore thyroid? Think De Quervain's!**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation of a midline, tender neck swelling following a sore throat is highly characteristic of subacute thyroiditis. This condition, often post-viral, causes inflammation and pain in the thyroid gland.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nSubacute thyroiditis, also known as De Quervain's thyroiditis, is typically a self-limiting inflammatory condition of the thyroid gland, often triggered by a viral infection (hence the preceding 'sore throat'). The inflammation leads to pain and tenderness in the thyroid, which is located in the midline of the neck. The tenderness is a key distinguishing feature, and the viral prodrome strongly supports this diagnosis over other thyroid pathologies.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Acute thyroiditis): Incorrect. While also post-infectious, acute thyroiditis is typically bacterial, more severe, often unilateral, and can lead to abscess formation. The description of a 'tender swelling' after a 'sore throat' is more aligned with the post-viral inflammatory process of subacute thyroiditis.\nOption B (Thyroglossal cyst): Incorrect. A thyroglossal cyst is a congenital anomaly, a midline neck mass that can become tender if infected. However, its primary presentation is not typically linked to a preceding 'sore throat' as a direct cause of the swelling, and it often moves with tongue protrusion, which is not mentioned.\nOption D (Toxic goiter): Incorrect. A toxic goiter refers to an enlarged thyroid gland causing hyperthyroidism. It is not typically acutely tender or painful, nor is its onset usually linked to a preceding sore throat. The primary symptoms relate to hyperthyroidism, not acute inflammation.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature             | Acute Thyroiditis (Suppurative) | Subacute Thyroiditis (De Quervain's) | Hashimoto's Thyroiditis (Chronic) |\n|---------------------|---------------------------------|--------------------------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| **Etiology**        | Bacterial infection             | Viral infection (post-viral)         | Autoimmune                        |\n| **Pain/Tenderness** | Severe, localized, often unilateral | Moderate to severe, diffuse, tender  | Usually painless                  |\n| **Onset**           | Rapid                           | Subacute, often post-URI             | Insidious                         |\n| **Thyroid Function**| Euthyroid, rarely hypo/hyper    | Transient hyperthyroid, then hypo, then euthyroid | Hypothyroid                       |\n| **ESR**             | Elevated                        | Markedly elevated                    | Normal to mildly elevated         |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: A painful, tender thyroid after a viral illness points directly to subacute thyroiditis.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, subacute thyroiditis typically presents as diffuse or patchy hypoechoic areas within the thyroid gland, often with decreased vascularity on Doppler imaging due to inflammation and edema.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nThe American Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015) and other general thyroid guidelines discuss inflammatory thyroid conditions, including subacute thyroiditis, outlining diagnostic criteria and management strategies.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Acute thyroiditis | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Thyroglossal cyst | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | Subacute thyroiditis | ✅ Correct |\n| D | Toxic goiter | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) Subacute thyroiditis** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
