    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 A healthy thyroid is just right, not too big, not too small.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe question asks for the average weight of a normal thyroid gland in an iodine-replete population. The correct answer, 18-20 gm, accurately reflects the typical size of a healthy adult thyroid under these optimal nutritional conditions.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nThe thyroid gland is a vital endocrine organ situated in the anterior neck, responsible for producing thyroid hormones. In regions with sufficient dietary iodine, the average adult thyroid gland typically weighs between 15-25 grams, with 18-20 grams being a commonly cited average. This weight ensures adequate functional tissue for hormone synthesis (T3 and T4) without compensatory hypertrophy, which would occur in iodine deficiency.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): 10-12 gm is generally considered on the lower end of normal or slightly small for an adult thyroid, potentially indicating hypoplasia or atrophy.\nOption B (Incorrect): 14-16 gm is also at the lower range of what is considered average for a healthy adult thyroid in an iodine-rich environment.\nOption D (Incorrect): 28-30 gm is typically indicative of a mildly enlarged thyroid or a small goiter, which would not be the average weight in a population with an iodine-rich diet.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Condition | Average Thyroid Weight | Notes |\n|---|---|---|\n| Normal adult (iodine-replete) | 15-25 gm (often cited 18-20 gm) | Healthy function, no hypertrophy |\n| Iodine deficiency | Can be >25 gm (goiter) | Compensatory hypertrophy to maximize iodine uptake |\n| Children | Smaller, increases with age | Varies significantly with age and body size |\n| Graves' disease | Often enlarged (>25 gm) | Hyperplasia due to autoimmune stimulation |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Normal adult thyroid weight is roughly 15-25 grams; know the average for iodine-replete regions.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, a normal adult thyroid gland typically measures about 4-6 cm in length, 1.5-2 cm in width, and 2-3 cm in anteroposterior diameter for each lobe. Intraoperatively, a normal gland is firm, reddish-brown, bilobed, and moves with swallowing, without palpable nodules or significant vascular engorgement.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015/2017/2023). While not directly stating an 'average weight,' these guidelines define goiter based on thyroid volume, with volumes >18-20 mL (which roughly correlates to grams) often considered enlarged.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | 10-12 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | 14-16 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | 18-20 gm | ✅ Correct |\n| D | 28-30 gm | ❌ Incorrect |\n\n**✅ Answer: C) 18-20 gm** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Medium** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
