    "markdown_debrief": "### SHARP 4.0 Cognitive & Surgical Debrief\n\n> **💡 Neuromas, habitus, and a thyroid lump? Think MEN-2B, it's a RET-rospective.**\n\n---\n\n## S — Set the Stage\nThe patient's presentation with medullary thyroid carcinoma, marfanoid habitus, and pathognomonic mucosal neuromas and medullated corneal nerve fibers unequivocally points to Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia type 2B (MEN-2B). This specific constellation of symptoms is diagnostic for the syndrome.\n\n## H — Highlight Excellence\nMEN-2B is an autosomal dominant disorder caused by a germline mutation in the RET proto-oncogene, distinct from MEN-2A by its specific phenotypic features. Key characteristics include medullary thyroid carcinoma (often aggressive and early onset), pheochromocytoma (less common than in MEN-2A but still present), and the unique mucocutaneous manifestations like mucosal neuromas (lips, tongue, eyelids) and a marfanoid habitus. The presence of medullated corneal nerve fibers is a highly specific diagnostic clue.\n\n## A — Address the Gaps\n\nOption A (Incorrect): Sporadic medullary carcinoma of thyroid occurs without the systemic features like neuromas, marfanoid habitus, or other endocrine tumors.\nOption B (Incorrect): Familial medullary carcinoma of thyroid is a variant of MTC that runs in families but typically lacks the extra-thyroidal manifestations such as neuromas and marfanoid habitus seen in MEN-2B. It's often considered a part of MEN-2A or a distinct entity without pheochromocytoma or hyperparathyroidism.\nOption C (Incorrect): MEN-2A includes medullary thyroid carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, and primary hyperparathyroidism, but it does not feature mucosal neuromas, marfanoid habitus, or medullated corneal nerve fibers.\n\n## R — Review Learning Points\n\n| Feature | MEN-1 (Wermer's) | MEN-2A (Sipple's) | MEN-2B |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Gene** | *MEN1* | *RET* | *RET* |\n| **Key Tumors** | Parathyroid adenoma, Pituitary adenoma, Pancreatic tumors | Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Primary Hyperparathyroidism | Medullary Thyroid Carcinoma, Pheochromocytoma, Mucosal Neuromas, Marfanoid Habitus |\n| **Unique Features** | Gastrinomas, Insulinomas | Hyperparathyroidism | Mucosal neuromas, Medullated corneal nerve fibers, Marfanoid habitus |\n| **MTC Aggressiveness** | N/A | Moderate | Highly aggressive, early onset |\n\n## P — Plan (Board Pearl)\nBoard Pearl: Mucosal neuromas + MTC + Marfanoid habitus = MEN-2B. Don't miss the RET mutation.\n\n---\n\n## 🔬 Imaging & Intraoperative Pearl\nOn ultrasound, the thyroid nodule would likely appear hypoechoic with microcalcifications, characteristic of medullary thyroid carcinoma. Intraoperatively, the thyroid gland might show bilateral involvement, and careful inspection for pheochromocytoma (adrenal mass on CT/MRI) would precede thyroidectomy.\n\n## 📋 Guideline Anchor\nAmerican Thyroid Association (ATA) Guidelines for the Management of Thyroid Nodules and Differentiated Thyroid Cancer (2015, updated 2023). These guidelines recommend genetic testing for RET mutations in all patients with MTC and prophylactic thyroidectomy for carriers of high-risk RET mutations.\n\n---\n\n### Answer Breakdown\n| Option | Text | Status |\n|--------|------|--------|\n| A | Sporadic medullary carcinoma of thyroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| B | Familial medullary carcinoma of thyroid | ❌ Incorrect |\n| C | MEN-2A | ❌ Incorrect |\n| D | MEN-2B | ✅ Correct |\n\n**✅ Answer: D) MEN-2B** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Difficulty: Hard** &nbsp;|&nbsp; **Source: Surgery Essence**\n",
